Build the deck component that renders the stacked card queue. FILE: src/components/core/AtRiskReview/AtRiskReviewDeck.tsx

IMPORTS NEEDED:
  import { AnimatePresence, motion } from 'framer-motion';
  import { useEffect, useRef, useState } from 'react';
  import { AtRiskReviewCard } from './AtRiskReviewCard';
  import type { CombinedItemType } from '@/components/core/Inventory';
  import type { ReviewDecision } from './useAtRiskReview';
  import { Swipe } from 'lucide-react'; // or a custom SVG hint

PROPS:
  interface AtRiskReviewDeckProps {
    queue: CombinedItemType[];
    onDecision: (itemId: number, decision: ReviewDecision) => void;
    isLoading?: boolean;
  }

STACKING LAYOUT:
Render the top 3 cards from queue simultaneously (or fewer if queue.length < 3). Each card is wrapped in a motion.div that is absolutely positioned. The container needs position: relative with min-h-[520px] to reserve enough vertical space.

Per-depth positioning (index 0 = top/front card):
  index 0: scale=1.00, y=0px,  zIndex=3, isTop=true
  index 1: scale=0.96, y=8px,  zIndex=2, isTop=false
  index 2: scale=0.92, y=16px, zIndex=1, isTop=false

Each wrapper motion.div gets: animate={{ scale, y, zIndex }} transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 300, damping: 30 }}
This means when the top card is removed (after onDecision), the remaining cards automatically animate into their new depth positions.

ANIMATEPRESENCE:
  <AnimatePresence mode='popLayout'>
    {queue.slice(0, 3).map((item, index) => (
      <motion.div
        key={item.id}
        className='absolute w-full'
        animate={{ scale: [1, 0.96, 0.92][index], y: [0, 8, 16][index], zIndex: [3, 2, 1][index] }}
        transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 300, damping: 30 }}
      >
        <AtRiskReviewCard
          item={item}
          isTop={index === 0}
          onDecision={(decision) => onDecision(item.id, decision)}
        />
      </motion.div>
    ))}
  </AnimatePresence>

EMPTY STATE: When queue.length === 0 and !isLoading, render null (parent AtRiskReviewModal switches to AtRiskReviewComplete screen).

SKELETON STATE: When isLoading=true, render a single placeholder:
  <div className='rounded-2xl animate-pulse bg-muted min-h-[400px] w-full max-w-sm mx-auto' />

SWIPE HINT: On first render, show a subtle animated hint after a 2-second delay. The hint is a small arrow icon that tweens left and right. Dismiss it (set to null) once ANY swipe decision is detected.
  - localStorage key: 'broccoli:atRiskReview:hintSeen'
  - On mount, if localStorage does NOT have this key, set a 2-second timeout to show the hint
  - Once any onDecision fires with type !== 'skipped' (first actual swipe), set localStorage key and dismiss hint
  - The hint renders as an absolutely-positioned overlay at the bottom-center of the deck, below the top card, so it does not interfere with dragging

DEPENDS ON: broccoli-dashboard-z4y (AtRiskReviewCard). Build alongside broccoli-dashboard-n5z (AtRiskReviewModal).

Update both service worker files to handle AT_RISK_REVIEW notification type — deep-link to the card deck when tapped.

FILES TO MODIFY:
  public/sw-push.js      (the canonical SW file served from public/)
  src/sw-custom.js       (the custom SW for dev/build — keep both in sync)

CHANGE 1 — Update notificationclick handler in BOTH files

Current behavior: all notifications open /app.
New behavior: notifications with data.type === 'AT_RISK_REVIEW' open /app?intent=review. If the app is already open, send postMessage instead of navigating.

Replace the existing notificationclick handler with:

  self.addEventListener('notificationclick', function(event) {
    console.log('[SW Push] Notification click received.');
    event.notification.close();

    const data = event.notification.data || {};
    const urlToOpen = data.type === 'AT_RISK_REVIEW' ? '/app?intent=review' : '/app';

    event.waitUntil(
      clients.matchAll({ type: 'window', includeUncontrolled: true })
        .then(function(clientList) {
          for (var i = 0; i < clientList.length; i++) {
            var client = clientList[i];
            if (client.url.includes('/app') && 'focus' in client) {
              if (data.type === 'AT_RISK_REVIEW') {
                client.postMessage({ type: 'OPEN_AT_RISK_REVIEW' });
              }
              return client.focus();
            }
          }
          if (clients.openWindow) {
            return clients.openWindow(urlToOpen);
          }
        })
    );
  });

WHY postMessage vs URL navigation:
- If the app is already open, navigating to a new URL would reload or disrupt the user's scroll. postMessage lets AtRiskReviewModal listen for OPEN_AT_RISK_REVIEW and open the deck in-place without navigation.
- If the app is closed, ?intent=review is the signal — AtRiskReviewModal reads it via useQueryState('intent') from nuqs on mount.

CHANGE 2 — Update tag in the push event handler in BOTH files

In the push event handler (where notificationData is built), update the tag field:

  // Old:
  tag: data.data?.itemId ? 'item-' + data.data.itemId : 'notification',

  // New:
  tag: data.data?.type === 'AT_RISK_REVIEW'
    ? 'at-risk-review'
    : data.data?.itemId
    ? 'item-' + data.data.itemId
    : 'notification',

This ensures if the cron fires twice the same day (edge case), the OS replaces the existing notification in the tray rather than stacking a duplicate.

TESTING (manual, in browser DevTools > Application > Push):
- Send a test push payload: { title: 'Test', body: 'Test', data: { type: 'AT_RISK_REVIEW' } }
- With app CLOSED: clicking notification should open /app?intent=review
- With app OPEN: clicking notification should NOT navigate; AtRiskReviewModal should open
- Existing ITEM_EXPIRING notifications (with data.itemId) must still work as before — verify tag and click URL are unaffected

NOTE: Both files need identical changes. Do NOT diverge them. The existing push event handler structure (data parsing, showNotification call) should remain intact — only the tag computation and notificationclick handler are changing.

DEPENDS ON: broccoli-dashboard-gcy (cron sets data.type = 'AT_RISK_REVIEW' in the push payload). SW changes are independent and can be done in parallel, but end-to-end testing requires the cron to be wired up.

