IMPLEMENTATION:

In AtRiskReviewCard.tsx:
  import { useReducedMotion } from 'framer-motion';

  const prefersReducedMotion = useReducedMotion();

  // Rotation: disable when prefers-reduced-motion is set
  const rotate = prefersReducedMotion
    ? 0
    : useTransform(dragX, [-200, 0, 200], [-15, 0, 15]);

  // Fly-out animation on button click: use fade instead of translate
  const handleEatenButtonClick = async () => {
    if ('vibrate' in navigator) navigator.vibrate(50);
    const animation = prefersReducedMotion
      ? { opacity: 0, transition: { duration: 0.2 } }
      : { x: 300, opacity: 0, transition: { duration: 0.3 } };
    await controls.start(animation);
    onDecision({ type: 'eaten' });
  };
  // Same pattern for handleDiscardButtonClick (fade to left vs translate)

  // Drag end: when motion is reduced, still commit the decision but skip the fly-out step
  // (the AnimatePresence exit on the deck wrapper handles removal)

In AtRiskReviewDeck.tsx:
  import { useReducedMotion } from 'framer-motion';

  const prefersReducedMotion = useReducedMotion();

  // Stacking animation: use instant layout update instead of spring
  // Pass prefersReducedMotion to each card wrapper's transition:
  transition={prefersReducedMotion
    ? { duration: 0 }
    : { type: 'spring', stiffness: 300, damping: 30 }}

  // AnimatePresence exit animation: cards should fade out instead of slide
  // (handled by AtRiskReviewCard's motion.div exit prop)

WHY framer-motion useReducedMotion:
framer-motion's useReducedMotion() reads the OS/browser prefers-reduced-motion media query reactively. It returns true when the user has enabled reduced motion in system settings. This is the idiomatic approach for framer-motion projects rather than a raw matchMedia call.

NOTE: This is a polish/accessibility task that should be done after the core animation code is working. The card and deck components must exist before this can be applied.

